│                                                                               │
│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                                   │
│                                                                               │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                               │
│ 1. Understanding the Issue:                                                   │
│ The crash occurs inside ScalarEvolution when SCEV::getType() is invoked on a  │
│ SCEVCouldNotCompute object. This indicates an earlier misuse: some code       │
│ passed a SCEV that represents 'could not compute' into an API that assumes    │
│ the SCEV is well-formed and typed. The reproducer uses a non-integral pointer │
│ address space ("ni:1" in the datalayout). Non-integral pointers cannot be     │
│ losslessly converted to integers. In tryToReuseLCSSAPhi(), we attempt to      │
│ convert a pointer induction SCEV (ExitSCEV) to an integer using               │
│ getPtrToIntExpr. For non-integral pointer types, getPtrToIntExpr returns      │
│ SCEVCouldNotCompute. The current code does not check for this and             │
│ unconditionally passes the resulting SCEV into getMinusSCEV, which then calls │
│ getType() on the RHS, triggering the unreachable assertion.                   │
│                                                                               │
│ 2. Analyzing opt's Log:                                                       │
│ The log shows the loop-idiom pass begins processing a countable loop and      │
│ immediately aborts with 'Attempt to use a SCEVCouldNotCompute object!' before │
│ any transformation messages (e.g. memset/memcpy recognition) appear. The      │
│ stack trace pinpoints the call chain: tryToReuseLCSSAPhi -> getMinusSCEV ->   │
│ SCEV::getType(). This proves the first mutation point is the attempted SCEV   │
│ difference calculation in tryToReuseLCSSAPhi, not a later transformation such │
│ as store pattern rewriting.                                                   │
│                                                                               │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                       │
│ The relevant code in SCEVExpander::tryToReuseLCSSAPhi:                        │
│   if (STy->isIntegerTy() && PhiTy->isPointerTy())                             │
│     ExitSCEV = SE.getPtrToIntExpr(ExitSCEV, STy);                             │
│   else if (S->getType() != PN.getType())                                      │
│     continue;                                                                 │
│ Immediately after, it computes Diff = SE.getMinusSCEV(S, ExitSCEV). If        │
│ getPtrToIntExpr fails (which happens for non-integral pointer address         │
│ spaces), it returns a SCEVCouldNotCompute object. There is no guard, so Diff  │
│ computation proceeds. getMinusSCEV assumes operands are valid typed SCEVs;    │
│ encountering SCEVCouldNotCompute leads to invoking getType(), which is        │
│ defined as unreachable for that sentinel object. Therefore, the misuse        │
│ resides in tryToReuseLCSSAPhi lacking a check after the pointer-to-int        │
│ conversion.                                                                   │
│ Alternative (broader) fixes could add a defensive early return inside         │
│ getMinusSCEV for CouldNotCompute operands, but per instructions we target the │
│ earliest incorrect use site. The assertion is correct; the earlier logic must │
│ avoid propagating CouldNotCompute.                                            │
│                                                                               │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s):                                                    │
│ File: llvm/lib/Transforms/Utils/ScalarEvolutionExpander.cpp                   │
│ Lines: 1239-1245 (the block handling the STy/PhiTy type adaptation)           │
│ Change: Wrap the pointer-to-int conversion in braces and add a check:         │
│   if (STy->isIntegerTy() && PhiTy->isPointerTy()) {                           │
│     ExitSCEV = SE.getPtrToIntExpr(ExitSCEV, STy);                             │
│     if (isa<SCEVCouldNotCompute>(ExitSCEV))                                   │
│       continue; // Cannot safely reuse this PHI; skip.                        │
│   } else if (S->getType() != PN.getType()) {                                  │
│     continue;                                                                 │
│   }                                                                           │
│ This prevents passing a SCEVCouldNotCompute to getMinusSCEV. It preserves     │
│ existing behavior for successful conversions and maintains the existing type  │
│ mismatch filtering logic.                                                     │
│ Rationale: Minimal, localized fix at first misuse site; avoids changing       │
│ broader SCEV semantics.                                                       │
│ Risk Assessment: Negligible. We only add a guard to skip reuse if conversion  │
│ fails. Downstream code already handles the nullptr return by proceeding with  │
│ normal expansion.                                                             │
│                                                                               │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                                │
│ The crash stems from failing to check for SCEVCouldNotCompute after           │
│ attempting a pointer-to-int SCEV conversion for a non-integral pointer.       │
│ Adding a guard in tryToReuseLCSSAPhi prevents invalid SCEV objects from       │
│ reaching getMinusSCEV, eliminating the assertion. This fix ensures loop-idiom │
│ recognition safely falls back to normal expansion without attempting illegal  │
│ reuse in non-integral pointer contexts.                                       │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                               │
│                                                                               │
