  "reason_thou": "1. Understanding the Issue:\nThe crash occurs inside
ScalarEvolution when SCEV::getType() is invoked on a SCEVCouldNotCompute object.
This indicates an earlier misuse: some code passed a SCEV that represents 'could
not compute' into an API that assumes the SCEV is well-formed and typed. The
reproducer uses a non-integral pointer address space (\"ni:1\" in the
datalayout). Non-integral pointers cannot be losslessly converted to integers. In
tryToReuseLCSSAPhi(), we attempt to convert a pointer induction SCEV (ExitSCEV)
to an integer using getPtrToIntExpr. For non-integral pointer types,
getPtrToIntExpr returns SCEVCouldNotCompute. The current code does not check for
this and unconditionally passes the resulting SCEV into getMinusSCEV, which then
calls getType() on the RHS, triggering the unreachable assertion.\n\n2. Analyzing
opt's Log:\nThe log shows the loop-idiom pass begins processing a countable loop
and immediately aborts with 'Attempt to use a SCEVCouldNotCompute object!' before
any transformation messages (e.g. memset/memcpy recognition) appear. The stack
trace pinpoints the call chain: tryToReuseLCSSAPhi -> getMinusSCEV ->
SCEV::getType(). This proves the first mutation point is the attempted SCEV
difference calculation in tryToReuseLCSSAPhi, not a later transformation such as
store pattern rewriting.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nThe relevant code in
SCEVExpander::tryToReuseLCSSAPhi:\n  if (STy->isIntegerTy() &&
PhiTy->isPointerTy())\n    ExitSCEV = SE.getPtrToIntExpr(ExitSCEV, STy);\n  else
if (S->getType() != PN.getType())\n    continue;\nImmediately after, it computes
Diff = SE.getMinusSCEV(S, ExitSCEV). If getPtrToIntExpr fails (which happens for
non-integral pointer address spaces), it returns a SCEVCouldNotCompute object.
There is no guard, so Diff computation proceeds. getMinusSCEV assumes operands
are valid typed SCEVs; encountering SCEVCouldNotCompute leads to invoking
getType(), which is defined as unreachable for that sentinel object. Therefore,
the misuse resides in tryToReuseLCSSAPhi lacking a check after the pointer-to-int
conversion.\nAlternative (broader) fixes could add a defensive early return
inside getMinusSCEV for CouldNotCompute operands, but per instructions we target
the earliest incorrect use site. The assertion is correct; the earlier logic must
avoid propagating CouldNotCompute.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\nFile:
llvm/lib/Transforms/Utils/ScalarEvolutionExpander.cpp\nLines: 1239-1245 (the
block handling the STy/PhiTy type adaptation)\nChange: Wrap the pointer-to-int
conversion in braces and add a check:\n  if (STy->isIntegerTy() &&
PhiTy->isPointerTy()) {\n    ExitSCEV = SE.getPtrToIntExpr(ExitSCEV, STy);\n
if (isa<SCEVCouldNotCompute>(ExitSCEV))\n      continue; // Cannot safely reuse
this PHI; skip.\n  } else if (S->getType() != PN.getType()) {\n    continue;\n
}\nThis prevents passing a SCEVCouldNotCompute to getMinusSCEV. It preserves
existing behavior for successful conversions and maintains the existing type
mismatch filtering logic.\nRationale: Minimal, localized fix at first misuse
site; avoids changing broader SCEV semantics.\nRisk Assessment: Negligible. We
only add a guard to skip reuse if conversion fails. Downstream code already
handles the nullptr return by proceeding with normal expansion.\n\n5.
Conclusion:\nThe crash stems from failing to check for SCEVCouldNotCompute after
attempting a pointer-to-int SCEV conversion for a non-integral pointer. Adding a
guard in tryToReuseLCSSAPhi prevents invalid SCEV objects from reaching
getMinusSCEV, eliminating the assertion. This fix ensures loop-idiom recognition
safely falls back to normal expansion without attempting illegal reuse in
non-integral pointer contexts.",
